ArrayList in Java

ArrayList is one of the most commonly used classes in Java.
It is a part of the List interface and is based on a dynamic array.

This means its size can grow or shrink automatically when elements are added or removed.

Why use ArrayList?

ArrayList is useful when:

you need fast access to elements
you work with indexed data
you don’t know the size of the collection in advance
Creating an ArrayList
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
Adding Elements
list.add("Apple");
list.add("Banana");
list.add("Orange");
Accessing Elements
String first = list.get(0); // Apple

ArrayList allows fast access by index.

Updating Elements
list.set(1, "Mango"); // replaces Banana
Removing Elements
list.remove(0);        // remove by index
list.remove("Orange"); // remove by value
Looping through ArrayList
for (String item : list) {
    System.out.println(item);
}
Important Features
maintains insertion order
allows duplicates
allows null values
resizable (dynamic size)
Performance
fast: get(index)
slower: add/remove in the middle (because elements shift)
When NOT to use ArrayList

ArrayList is not the best choice when:

you frequently insert/remove elements in the middle
you need very fast modifications

In such cases, LinkedList might be a better option.

Summary
ArrayList is a dynamic array
provides fast access by index
easy to use and very flexible
best for reading data more than modifying it
